article.headline: San Diego State 65, BYU 61
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A game billed as a showdown between two senior big men came down to a freshman guard. Brandon Heath hit a go-ahead 3-pointer with 1:24 left, then had two steals in the final 30 seconds to help preserve San Diego State's 65-61 win over Brigham Young on Monday night in the Mountain West Conference opener for both teams. "Brandon is a guy who loves -- sometimes too much -- to take the big shot," coach Steve Fisher said. "He's proven he can hit them." San Diego State (10-6) blew a 10-point lead in the closing minutes and saw its leading scorer, senior forward Aerick Sanders, foul out with 3:22 left. The Aztecs still beat the Cougars (10-4), the MWC preseason favorites, thanks to Heath. BYU took a 61-59 lead on a layup by Luiz Lemes with 1:44 left. Heath had a shot blocked by Mike Hall, and the ball went out of bounds. Three seconds later, Heath hit a 3-pointer from the left corner to give the Aztecs a 62-61 lead. It was just the fourth basket for the Aztecs since they took a 54-44 lead on Chris Walton's 3-pointer with 9:06 to play. Heath said point guard Wesley Stokes encouraged him to keep shooting after getting his shot blocked. "There's no time to hesitate," Heath said. "He's a big-time player," Stokes said. "He knows we expect big things from him. We don't expect him to be scared. He's not really a freshman anymore." BYU committed turnovers on its last three possessions, and Heath came up with two of them. Heath also made a free throw with 26 seconds left, and Trimaine Davis made a fast-break layup with 12 seconds left. "It's very disappointing not to get a shot off," BYU's Mark Bigelow said. "We just didn't make plays down the stretch and they did." Sanders scored a game-high 18 points before drawing his fifth foul with 3:22 left, against BYU center Rafael Araujo going for a rebound. Araujo, the MWC's leading scorer, made both free throws to tie it at 59. Stokes scored 15 for SDSU, Heath had 13 and Walton 12. BYU also had four players in double figures, led by Mike Hall with 15 and Mark Bigelow 14. Araujo, averaging 20.8 coming in, scored just 12 points, none in the first half. It was his second-lowest total of the season. Araujo had a game-high 13 rebounds. Araujo, who's bigger and stronger than Sanders, took only two shots in the first half, missing both. His first points came in the opening minute of the second half, when his putback gave BYU a 35-31 lead.
